Buxhowden. During this in- terregnum we begin a very original and inter- esting series of maneuvers. Our aim is no longer, as it should be, to avoid or attack the enemy, but solely to avoid General Buxhowden who by right of seniority should be our chief. 
So energetically do we pursue this aim that aft- er crossing an unfordable river we burn the bridges to separate ourselves from our enemy, who at the moment is not Bonaparte but Bux- howden. General Buxhowden was all but at- tacked
